===Etymology===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|かばん}}
{{wp|ja:}}

Possibly derived from {{der|ja|zh|夾板|sort=かばん}} or {{m|zh|夾槾|tr=jiāmàn||[[board]]s for [[pressing]] or [[holding]] [[thing]]s [[together]]}},<ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref> modern {{cog|nan|-}} reading ''kiap-pán''.

Some references mention a possible borrowing from [[Belgian]] {{cog|nl|kabas}} with an ostensible meaning of {{m|en|bag}}.<ref name="DDJS">{{R:Digital-Daijisen}}</ref>  However, this is problematic on both semantic grounds, as Dutch sources indicate that the word means not {{m|en|bag}} but rather {{m|en|basket}}, in keeping with its apparent derivation from {{cog|fr|cabas||basket}};<ref>From the search results for "kabas" at the ''Instituut voor de Nederlandse Taal'' website: [https://gtb.ivdnt.org/iWDB/search?actie=article&wdb=WNT&id=M029363&lemmodern=kabas&domein=0&conc=true 1], [https://gtb.ivdnt.org/iWDB/search?actie=article&wdb=WNT&id=M029363&lemmodern=kabas&Betekenis_id=M029363.bet.1 2]</ref> and on phonological grounds, as there is no clear mechanism for converting the final <code>/s/</code> in the Dutch into the final <code>/n/</code> in the Japanese, especially considering how relatively recently the Japanese word ''kaban'' first appears.

The original meaning of the kanji {{m|ja|鞄#Kanji|鞄}} referred to [[tanned]] [[leather]] or a [[tanner]] who produces such material.<ref name="KDJ"/><ref name="DDJS"/>  The native reading (''{{ll|ja|訓読み|kun'yomi}}'') ''kaban'' only appears from the {{w|Meiji period}} (1868–1912).<ref name="KDJ"/>

First attested with this reading to a work from 1877;<ref name="KDJ"/> over the period of roughly 1877–1887, this word grew in popularity and displaced the previous term {{m|ja|胴乱|tr=dōran||[[satchel]]}}.<ref name="KDJ"/><ref>{{R:Nipponica}}</ref>

